            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-12-30T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-12-30T01:00:00-05:00" n="93" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d93">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">851<gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss>.01/12–3049:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Saigon</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Abbott</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-12-30T14:00:00+08:00">December 30, 1949—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>474. Pass Paris.<note n="1" xml:id="d93fn1">This was done the same day.</note>
                    Pouched Hanoi. In hectic rush ending 2:30 a. m. December 29 agreement reached on
                    about 30 conventions signed today covering transfer powers in following fields:
                    justice, military, economics, finance, public works, cultural affairs, public
                    health, information, personnel.</p>
                <p>Justice convention provides for mixed tribunals for criminal and civil cases
                    involving citizens of French Union and privileged foreigners (Chinese).
                    Presidents mixed courts and state attorneys to be appointed mutual agreement
                    French Vietnam.</p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Sûreté</hi> entirely transferred Vietnam in principle but
                    French <hi rend="italic">Sûreté</hi> will continue control immigration and
                    interstate travel until completion <pb facs="0130" n="116" xml:id="pg_116"/> of
                    forthcoming interstate conference, and validate Viet Government passports and
                    travel authorizations until Vietnam achieves international recognition.
                    Counter-espionage and anti-terrorist activities of French <hi rend="italic">Sûreté</hi> on behalf French Union troops to continue until restoration of
                    order. Only permanent <hi rend="italic">Sûreté</hi> organization will be liaison
                    mission with Vietnam <hi rend="italic">Sûreté</hi> to coordinate security French
                    Union. Viets may have similar mission in Paris.</p>
                <p>Permanent military convention covers bases for and activities of French Union
                    troops. Described by Nguyen Phan Long as more liberal than US–Philippine
                    agreement. Separate agreement covers situation until peace and order
                    restored.</p>
                <p>Above based on summary and analysis furnished Consulate General by French and
                    press interview Nguyen Phan Long. No information re date publication actual
                    texts.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Abbott</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
